<font color="#FF0000">HK VIETNAME NOW REFUGEES-UN</font><br>
<tt>Mon Jun  2 23:08:12 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
I just pulled this off the internet edition of the Hong Kong Morning Post:<br><br>
&quot;EMMA BATHA <br>
Former Vietnamese soldiers who fought on the side of the United States have been declared refugees following a surprise about-turn by the United Nations, it was revealed yesterday.<br><br>
A group of 31 asylum-seekers and their families - about 170 people - are expected to be resettled in America following secret negotiations.<br><br>
American immigration officers are expected to begin interviews with them in the next two days.<br><br>
If the refugees are accepted, they are likely to leave Hong Kong before the handover.<br><br>
Some of the Vietnamese were badly wounded during the war and others were tortured or sent to re-education camp afterwards.<br><br>
Almost all are Nungs, an ethnic people renowned for being fiercely anti-communist.<br><br>
They were recruited by the US Government during the Vietnam<br>
War. Many were part of the US special forces, commonly known<br>
as the Green Berets.<br><br>
Some were paratroopers who were sent on dangerous<br>
reconnaissance missions, while others guarded US advisers and military. After the fall of Saigon in 1975, they hid their history from the authorities.<br><br>
But when they came to Hong Kong up to seven years ago they<br>
were refused refugee status.<br><br>
The discussions over the past fortnight have been kept secret.<br><br>
The change of heart follows heavy lobbying by US veterans,<br>
some of whom visited the territory last week.<br><br>
The UN High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) in Hong Kong and Geneva refused to comment last night.<br><br>
Refugee lawyer Wanyong Austin said: &quot;We're very pleased. They would face special danger if they returned to Vietnam. They have not yet paid a 'blood debt' and the fact they have kept their past a secret makes their offence more serious in the eyes of the Vietnamese authorities.<br><br>
&quot;One of the things that has brought this about is the lobbying efforts by veterans in the US on behalf of their former army buddies - that's really made the difference. The special forces guys have been flooding the Internet as well as lobbying congressmen and senators,&quot; Ms Austin said.<br><br>
The US State Department told the UNHCR early in May it would<br>
be willing to consider the cases of the 31 people if they were declared refugees.<br><br>
A spokesman said: &quot;The whole process has been expedited. But we cannot make a guarantee we can settle them. That can only be done by the Immigration and Naturalisation Service.&quot;<br><br>
The Vietnamese are expected to be released from High Island<br>
camp in a couple of days. They will live in the open centres at New Horizons, or Pillar Point, until they leave.&quot;<br><br>
To the Green Beenies who helped:  WELL DONE!
